<dl id="n53100i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53100i">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53100i"> 100(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> lorimer, pewterer upholders / paperstainer innholder / bowyers salter / fletchers girdler / cordwainer / leatherseller ~ <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53100i"><li>FW 312.35ff </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/lexma.htm#n53100i">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/l39ma.htm#n53100i">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53100i">MS BL 47479-169</ms> </li><li>JJA 54:259 <a name="mad6" href="../../ff/fdra/mda.htm#mad6">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ma/mad6.htm#n53100i">Draft: II.3&sect;1.6</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Livery Companies]</font>: <font color="green">[These were survivals of the civic life of medieval London where, for more than six hundred years they formed the active centre of the trade, social and religious life of the merchants and manufacturers of the City. Each was incorporated by an Ordinanace of the Mayor and Aldermen of the City of London, and this was generally followed by a Royal Charter or Act of Parliament. They were granted specific powers, such as of search and seizure, and a livery or costume to distinguish themselves at important functions. They were many and included the <mark>Lorimers</mark> &mdash; bit, stirrup and bow makers; the Pewterers &mdash; those who worked in pewter; the <mark>Upholders</mark>, also called Fripperers, these were the upholsterers, undertakers and dealers in small wares; the <mark>Paper-Stainers</mark> &mdash; artists and designers [a picture on canvas was known as a &lsquo;stained cloth&rsquo;]</font>; the <mark>Innholders</mark> or Hostellers; the <mark>Bowyers</mark> &mdash; those who made bows; the <mark>Salters</mark>, who used salt in the preservation of meat and fish; the <mark>Fletchers</mark>, who complimented the Bowyers by making arrows or fletches; the <mark>Girdlers</mark> &mdash; girdle and belt makers; the <mark>Cordwainers</mark>, who dealt in leather and made shoes; the <mark>Leathersellers</mark>, Shipwrights, and Skinners &mdash; dealers in felt and pelts; and the Mercers, the primary company, who dealt in cloths and colours. The Parish Clerks, though an influential company, were never granted livery, while the Weavers were.] <small> Athelstan Ridgway, ed. <a name="RDOD" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RDOD"><cite title="source">A Dictionary of Dates</cite></a> (1932) L</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
